<content>
<h1>Sebaldus Heyden Fōrmulae Puerīlium Colloquiōrum</h1>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus I</h2>
<head>Salūtātiō Mātūtīna</head>
<en-head>Morning Greeting</en-head>
<speakers>Andrēās, !Balthasar.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>An. Bonus dies.</p>
<en-p>Good day.</en-p>
<p>Ba. Deō grātiās.</p>
<en-p>Thank God.</en-p>
<p>An. Optō tibi bonum diem.</p>
<en-p>I hope you have a good day.</en-p>
<p>Ba. Tālem et tibi precor.</p>
<en-p>Such I also pray for you.</en-p>
<p>An. Bene sit tibi hōc diē.</p>
<en-p>May everything go well for you today.</en-p>
<p>Ba. Nec tibi male sit.</p>
<en-p>And not badly for you.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus II</h2>
<head>Salūtātiō Merīdiāna</head>
<en-head>Noon Greeting</en-head>
<speakers>!Blāsius, Clēmēns.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Bl. Salve Clēmēns.</p>
<en-p>Hello, Clement.</en-p>
<p>Cl. Salvē et tū.</p>
<en-p>Hello to you, too.</en-p>
<p>Bl. Salvē plūrimum.</p>
<en-p>I hope you are very well.</en-p>
<p>Cl. Et tū tantundem salvē.</p>
<en-p>And I hope you are just as well.</en-p>
<p>Bl. Salvus sīs tū.</p>
<en-p>May you be well.</en-p>
<p>Cl. Tū quoque salvē.</p>
<en-p>And you also be well.</en-p>
<p>Bl. Salūtem tibi precor.</p>
<en-p>I pray that you have good health.</en-p>
<p>Cl. Eandem et tibi optō.</p>
<en-p>And I hope the same for you.</en-p>
<p>Bl. Salūte tē impertior.</p>
<en-p>I impart health to you.</en-p>
<p>Cl. Et ego quoque tē.</p>
<en-p>And I also to you.</en-p>
<p>Bl. Iubeō tē salvēre.</p>
<en-p>I command you to be well.</en-p>
<p>Cl. Tē quoque ego.</p>
<en-p>I also command you.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus III</h2>
<head>Salūtātiō Vespertīna</head>
<en-head>Evening Greeting</en-head>
<speakers>!Carolus, Dēmētrius.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ca. Bonus vesper.</p>
<en-p>Good evening.</en-p>
<p>De. Grātia Deō.</p>
<en-p>Thanks be to God.</en-p>
<p>Ca. Bonum sērum.</p>
<en-p>Good twilight.</en-p>
<p>De. Laus Creātōrī.</p>
<en-p>Praise be to the Creator.</en-p>
<p>Ca. Hic vesper fēlīx sit tibi.</p>
<en-p>May this evening be happy for you.</en-p>
<p>De. Nec tibi infēlīx sit.</p>
<en-p>And may it not be unhappy for you.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus IV</h2>
<head>Sub Prīmam Facem Noctis</head>
<en-head>At the Night’s First Watch</en-head>
<speakers>!Detius, !Eustachius.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>De. Sit tibi haec nox fēlīx.</p>
<en-p>May this night be happy for you.</en-p>
<p>Eu. Et tibi fausta haec sit.</p>
<en-p>And may it be fortunate for you.</en-p>
<p>De. Faustam dēgās noctem.</p>
<en-p>May you spend a fortunate night.</en-p>
<p>Eu. Tū quoque nōn infaustam.</p>
<en-p>You also, not an unfortunate one.</en-p>
<p>De. Nox istaec vōbīs commodet.</p>
<en-p>May this your night go well for you.</en-p>
<p>Eu. Et tibi nōn incommodet.</p>
<en-p>And may it non go badly for you.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus V</h2>
<head>Dum Ītur Cubitum</head>
<en-head>While Going to Bed</en-head>
<speakers>Fēlīx, !Gaspar.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Fē. Quota est hōra?</p>
<en-p>What time is it?</en-p>
<p>Ga. Sonuit tertiam.</p>
<en-p>The third hour has rung.</en-p>
<p>Fē. Eundum est cubitum.</p>
<en-p>We should go to bed.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Nōn !dormītūriō.</p>
<en-p>I won’t go to sleep.</en-p>
<p>Fē. At ego oppidō.</p>
<en-p>But I will, for sure.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Tū eās cubitum.</p>
<en-p>You can go to bed.</en-p>
<p>Fē. Quid tū autem āgēs?</p>
<en-p>So what are you gonna do?</en-p>
<p>Ga. Pergam legere.</p>
<en-p>I’ll keep reading.</en-p>
<p>Fē. Mālō quiēscere.</p>
<en-p>I’d rather rest.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Facesse hinc, Endymiōn.</p>
<en-p>Do it somewhere else, Endymion.</en-p>
<p>Fē. Haud tē impedīverō.</p>
<en-p>I won’t stop you from anything.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus VI</h2>
<head>Dum Redītur Cubitū</head>
<en-head>While Getting Up</en-head>
<speakers>!Gabriel, Henrīcus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ga. Heus, expergīscere.</p>
<en-p>Hey, get going.</en-p>
<p>He. Sine ut dormiam.</p>
<en-p>Let me sleep.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Surgendī tempus est.</p>
<en-p>It’s time to get up.</en-p>
<p>He. Nōndum dīlūxit.</p>
<en-p>It’s not light yet.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Aperī oculōs.</p>
<en-p>Open your eyes.</en-p>
<p>He. Adhūc gravantur somnō.</p>
<en-p>They’re still heavy with sleep.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Es glīre somnolentior.</p>
<en-p>You’re sleepier than a dormouse.</en-p>
<p>He. Rogō nē sīs molestus.</p>
<en-p>I’m asking you to quit being annoying.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Nōn pudet tē, asine?</p>
<en-p>Aren’t you ashamed, you donkey?</en-p>
<p>He. Cuius mē pudeat?</p>
<en-p>What should I be ashamed of?</en-p>
<p>Ga. In multam lūcem stertere.</p>
<en-p>Snoring into broad daylight.</en-p>
<p>He. Quotam hōram sonuit?</p>
<en-p>What time has it rung?</en-p>
<p>Ga. Iam imminet prīma.</p>
<en-p>The first hour is coming up.</en-p>
<p>He. Adhūc parum dormiam.</p>
<en-p>I’ll still sleep a little.</en-p>
<p>Ga. Quīn surgis, piger?</p>
<en-p>Why don’t you get up, you bum?</en-p>
<p>He. Quōmodo tam māne?</p>
<en-p>How can I so early?</en-p>
<p>Ga. Mox fuste tē excitābō.</p>
<en-p>I’m gonna wake you up with a stick soon.</en-p>
<p>He. Iam surgō, parce precor.</p>
<en-p>I’m getting up now; please, let me be.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus VII</h2>
<head>Dum Ītur Ad Scholam</head>
<en-head>While Heading for School</en-head>
<speakers>Hannō, Iōannēs.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ha. Heu, quid facimus?</p>
<en-p>Hey, what are we doing?</en-p>
<p>Iō. Cūr sīc vōciferās?</p>
<en-p>Why are you shouting?</en-p>
<p>Ha. Nimis diū dormīvī.</p>
<en-p>I slept too long.</en-p>
<p>Iō. Quid ita? Quid times?</p>
<en-p>So what? What are you afraid of?</en-p>
<p>Ha. Tempus praescrīptum trānsiit.</p>
<en-p>The assigned time has gone by.</en-p>
<p>Iō. Quod tempus dīcis?</p>
<en-p>What time are you talking about?</en-p>
<p>Ha. Hōram prīmam.</p>
<en-p>The first hour.</en-p>
<p>Iō. Tū certē falleris.</p>
<en-p>You’re definitely wrong.</en-p>
<p>Ha. Tamen audīvī.</p>
<en-p>But I heard it.</en-p>
<p>Iō. Nōn rēctē audīstī.</p>
<en-p>You didn’t hear it right.</en-p>
<p>Ha. Quotam tū audīstī?</p>
<en-p>What hour did you hear?</en-p>
<p>Iō. Audīvī ultimam.</p>
<en-p>I heard the last one.</en-p>
<p>Ha. Quota ea est?</p>
<en-p>Which one is that?</en-p>
<p>Iō. Duodecima.</p>
<en-p>The twelfth.</en-p>
<p>Ha. Utinam vērum sit.</p>
<en-p>I hope it’s true.</en-p>
<p>Iō. Nōn est quod dubitēs.</p>
<en-p>There’s no reason to doubt it.</en-p>
<p>Ha. Oppidō laetor.</p>
<en-p>I’m sure glad.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus VIII</h2>
<head>Inter Eundum In Scholam</head>
<en-head>While Going to School</en-head>
<speakers>!Iodocus, !Kiliānus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Io. Heus heus, manē.</p>
<en-p>Hey, wait.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Quid vīs? Cūr maneam?</p>
<en-p>What do you want? Why should I wait?</en-p>
<p>Io. Est quod tēcum loquar.</p>
<en-p>There’s something I need to tell you.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Modo nōn vacat.</p>
<en-p>There’s no time just now.</en-p>
<p>Io. Tantillum pernegēs?</p>
<en-p>You refuse such a little thing?</en-p>
<p>Ki. Mitte mē modo.</p>
<en-p>Just let me go.</en-p>
<p>Io. Nōn tē dīmittam.</p>
<en-p>I won’t let you go.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Ēnecās mē, furcifer.</p>
<en-p>You’re killing me, you jerk.</en-p>
<p>Io. Tantum verbum audī.</p>
<en-p>Listen to just one word.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Ecquid meā rēfert?</p>
<en-p>Is it really something that concerns me?</en-p>
<p>Io. Per multum scīlicet.</p>
<en-p>A whole lot, definitely.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Quid negōtiī est? dīc.</p>
<en-p>What's the problem? Tell me.</en-p>
<p>Io. Dīcam, modo dēs fidem.</p>
<en-p>I’ll tell you, just promise.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Quam fidem darem?</p>
<en-p>What should I promise?</en-p>
<p>Io. Tē nōn fore invidum.</p>
<en-p>That you won’t be a jerk about it.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Dō fidem, fīdus erō.</p>
<en-p>I promise; I’ll be fair.</en-p>
<p>Io. Adhibē hūc aurem.</p>
<en-p>Get your ear close here.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Quid aurem? clārē dīc.</p>
<en-p>Why my ear? Say it out loud.</en-p>
<p>Io. Arcāna rēs est.</p>
<en-p>It’s a private thing.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Tamen sōlī sumus.</p>
<en-p>But we’re alone.</en-p>
<p>Io. Clārē nōn dīcam.</p>
<en-p>I won’t say it out loud.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Lūdificāris nunc mē.</p>
<en-p>Now you’re making fun of me.</en-p>
<p>Io. Id est quod voluī.</p>
<en-p>That’s what I wanted.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Haud impūnē hōc ferēs.</p>
<en-p>You won’t get away with this.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus IX</h2>
<head>Inter Discendum In Schola</head>
<speakers>Kilianus, Lampertus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ki. Heus tu huc sede.</p>
<en-p>Hey, sit over here.</en-p>
<p>La. Quid istic facerem?</p>
<en-p>What would I do over there?</en-p>
<p>Ki. Discamus simul.</p>
<en-p>Let’s learn together.</en-p>
<p>La. Rem gratam offers.</p>
<en-p>That’s a nice suggestion.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Alter alterum doceat.</p>
<en-p>Let one teach the other.</en-p>
<p>La. Perlubens pareo.</p>
<en-p>I am totally ready.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Quidnam tu discis?</p>
<en-p>What are you learning, anyway?</en-p>
<p>La. Disco legere.</p>
<en-p>I’m learning to read.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Ubi nunc legis?</p>
<en-p>Where are you reading now?</en-p>
<p>La. In hoc folio.</p>
<en-p>On this sheet.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Scis lectionem?</p>
<en-p>Do you know the reading?</en-p>
<p>La. Non admodum prompte.</p>
<en-p>Not quickly enough.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Quoties recitasti?</p>
<en-p>How many times have you recited it?</en-p>
<p>La. Recitavi semel (I), bis (II), ter (III), quater (IIII).</p>
<en-p>I’ve recited it once, twice, thrice, four times.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Cuinam recitasti?</p>
<en-p>Who did you recite it to?</en-p>
<p>La. Rectori scholae.</p>
<en-p>To the principal.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Si quid nescis, roga.</p>
<en-p>If you don’t know something, ask.</en-p>
<p>La. Qui hoc legam?</p>
<en-p>How should I read this?</en-p>
<p>Ki. Collige litteras.</p>
<en-p>Sound out the letters.</en-p>
<p>La. Tu me observa.</p>
<en-p>Watch me.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Ut haesitas lingua?</p>
<en-p>Why are you hesitant in your speech?</en-p>
<p>La. Sic assuetus sum.</p>
<en-p>That’s what I’m used to.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Desuesce rursus.</p>
<en-p>Get unused to it.</en-p>
<p>La. Pergam legere.</p>
<en-p>I’ll keep reading.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Iam verba praecipitas.</p>
<en-p>Now you’re rushing through the words.</en-p>
<p>La. Tu melius doce.</p>
<en-p>Teach me better.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Sic distincte legas.</p>
<en-p>You should read distinctly, like this.</en-p>
<p>La. Tam clare haud queo.</p>
<en-p>I can’t read that clearly.</en-p>
<p>Ki. Usu addisce.</p>
<en-p>Learn it by practicing.</en-p>
<p>La. Tentabo quid possim.</p>
<en-p>I’ll see what I can do.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus X</h2>
<head>De Cavendis In Schola Coricaeis</head>
<en-head>Beware the Tattle-Tales in School</en-head>
<speakers>Lucas, Marcus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Lu. Cur tu sic mutis?</p>
<en-p>Why are you so quiet?</en-p>
<p>Ma. Non audeo loqui.</p>
<en-p>I don’t dare speak.</en-p>
<p>Lu. Quis te prohibet?</p>
<en-p>Who’s telling you not to?</en-p>
<p>Ma. Praeceptor noster.</p>
<en-p>Our teacher.</en-p>
<p>Lu. Tamen is non adest.</p>
<en-p>But he’s not here.</en-p>
<p>Ma. At Coricaei adsunt.</p>
<en-p>But the tattle-tales are here.</en-p>
<p>Lu. Quos Coricaeos dicis?</p>
<en-p>What tattle-tales are you talking about?</en-p>
<p>Ma. Qui clanculum nos signant.</p>
<en-p>The ones who are secretly writing notes about us.</en-p>
<p>Lu. Nullum ex his nosti?</p>
<en-p>You don’t know any of them?</en-p>
<p>Ma. Qui ego noscerem?</p>
<en-p>How would I know them?</en-p>
<p>Lu. Tam caute rem agunt?</p>
<en-p>They do it so cautiously?</en-p>
<p>Ma. Ea est illis astutia.</p>
<en-p>That’s their sneakiness.</en-p>
<p>Lu. Tu loquere Latine.</p>
<en-p>Speak in Latin.</en-p>
<p>Ma. Quam vellem si scirem.</p>
<en-p>I would, if I knew how.</en-p>
<p>Lu. At sic addisces citius.</p>
<en-p>But that way you’ll learn faster.</en-p>
<p>Ma. Hac spe dulcescit ferula.</p>
<en-p>By this hope, the rod gets sweet.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XI</h2>
<head>De Ferula</head>
<en-head>The Rod</en-head>
<speakers>Martinus, Nicolaus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ma. Quis hic eiulat?</p>
<en-p>Who’s over here crying?</en-p>
<p>Ni. Ego sum miser.</p>
<en-p>I’m so miserable.</en-p>
<p>Ma. Quo pacto miser es?</p>
<en-p>What are you miserable about?</en-p>
<p>Ni. Virgis caesus sum.</p>
<en-p>I got beaten by whips.</en-p>
<p>Ma. Quid commeruisti?</p>
<en-p>What did you do wrong?</en-p>
<p>Ni. Nihil didiceram.</p>
<en-p>I hadn’t learned anything.</en-p>
<p>Ma. Merito caesus es.</p>
<en-p>You were beaten deservedly.</en-p>
<p>Ni. Etiam tu me ludis?</p>
<en-p>Are you making fun of me, too?</en-p>
<p>Ma. Cur autem non didiceras?</p>
<en-p>But why hadn’t you learned anything?</en-p>
<p>Ni. Posthac ero cautior.</p>
<en-p>I’ll be more careful after this.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XII</h2>
<head>De Ientaculo</head>
<en-head>Breakfast</en-head>
<speakers>Naevius, Osualdus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Næ. Quo tu nunc abis?</p>
<en-p>Where are you going off to?</en-p>
<p>Os. Domum me confero.</p>
<en-p>I’m heading home.</en-p>
<p>Næ. Quid domi ages?</p>
<en-p>What’ll you do at home?</en-p>
<p>Os. Sumam ientaculum.</p>
<en-p>I eating breakfast.</en-p>
<p>Næ. Quanam iturus es?</p>
<en-p>Which way are you gonna go?</en-p>
<p>Os. Hac per forum.</p>
<en-p>This way, through the square.</en-p>
<p>Næ. Comitabor te.</p>
<en-p>I’ll go with you.</en-p>
<p>Os. Nihil opus est.</p>
<en-p>It’s not necessary.</en-p>
<p>Næ. Aversaris me?</p>
<en-p>Are you avoiding me?</en-p>
<p>Os. Non, sed parco.</p>
<en-p>No, but I am giving you a break.</en-p>
<p>Næ. Nihil est quod agam.</p>
<en-p>There’s nothing else I’d do.</en-p>
<p>Os. Lubens te accipio.</p>
<en-p>I’ll gladly take you along.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XIII</h2>
<head>De Reditu A Ientaculo</head>
<en-head>Returning from Breakfast</en-head>
<speakers>Onophrius, Paulus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>On. Unde nobis redis?</p>
<en-p>Where are you coming back from?</en-p>
<p>Pa. A ientaculo.</p>
<en-p>From breakfast.</en-p>
<p>On. Ubi ientasti?</p>
<en-p>Where did you eat breakfast.</en-p>
<p>Pa. Rogas? domi meae.</p>
<en-p>You’re asking? At my house.</en-p>
<p>On. Quid ientasti?</p>
<en-p>What did you eat for breakfast?</en-p>
<p>Pa. Panem iurulentum.</p>
<en-p>A trencher.</en-p>
<p>On. Quis tecum ientavit?</p>
<en-p>Who ate breakfast with you?</en-p>
<p>Pa. Tota familia.</p>
<en-p>The whole family.</en-p>
<p>On. Nihil mihi adfers?</p>
<en-p>You’re not bringing me anything?</en-p>
<p>Pa. Quid adferrem tibi?</p>
<en-p>What should I bring you?</en-p>
<p>On. Frustum panis.</p>
<en-p>A bread crust.</en-p>
<p>Pa. Panem quidem habeo.</p>
<en-p>I do have bread.</en-p>
<p>On. Cedo mihi partem.</p>
<en-p>Give me a piece.</en-p>
<p>Pa. Accipe dimidium.</p>
<en-p>Take half.</en-p>
<p>On. Ago tibi gratias.</p>
<en-p>Thank you.</en-p>
<p>Pa. Non age, sed refer.</p>
<en-p>Don’t thank; return the favor.</en-p>
<p>On. Non est unde referam.</p>
<en-p>There’s nothing I can return it with.</en-p>
<p>Pa. Non semper egebis.</p>
<en-p>You won’t always be needy.</en-p>
<p>On. Gratum me reperies.</p>
<en-p>You’ll find me grateful.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XIV</h2>
<head>De Parando Calamo</head>
<en-head>Getting a Pen Ready</en-head>
<speakers>Petrus, Quirinus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Pe. Para mihi hanc pennam.</p>
<en-p>Get this pen ready for me.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Est tibi cultellus?</p>
<en-p>Do you have a penknife?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Est, sed valde hebes.</p>
<en-p>I do, but it’s very blunt.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Acutiorem adfer.</p>
<en-p>Bring a sharper one.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Ubi accipiam?</p>
<en-p>Where will I get one?</en-p>
<p>Qu. Utendum expete.</p>
<en-p>Ask to use one.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Adfero, utere.</p>
<en-p>I’ve got one; use it.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Vis crassam, an tenuem?</p>
<en-p>Do you want it thick, or thin?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Mediam volo.</p>
<en-p>I want it medium.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Da atramentum.</p>
<en-p>Give me some ink.</en-p>
<p>Pe. En atramentarium.</p>
<en-p>Here’s some ink.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Da quoque papyrum.</p>
<en-p>Give me some paper, too.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Et haec in promptu est.</p>
<en-p>And here’s some ready.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Papyrus perfluit.</p>
<en-p>The paper is soaking through.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Non habeo aliam.</p>
<en-p>I don’t have another sheet.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Quid vis ut scribam?</p>
<en-p>What do you want me to write?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Praescribe literas.</p>
<en-p>Write the letters first.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Tu imitaberis?</p>
<en-p>You will imitate them?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Ita, in hoc peto.</p>
<en-p>Yes, that’s what I’m asking for.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Saepe exscribe.</p>
<en-p>Write them out often.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Faciam ut iubes.</p>
<en-p>I will do as you say.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XV</h2>
<head>Inter Redeundum A Schola</head>
<en-head>While Returning Back From School</en-head>
<speakers>Quintius, Rudolphus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Qu. Ut tecum agitur?</p>
<en-p>How’s it going with you?</en-p>
<p>Ru. Bene mecum agitur.</p>
<en-p>It’s going well with me.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Id lubens audio.</p>
<en-p>I’m glad to hear it.</en-p>
<p>Ru. Gratiam habeo.</p>
<en-p>Thank you.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Ubi iam fuisti?</p>
<en-p>Where have you been, now?</en-p>
<p>Ru. In ludo litterario.</p>
<en-p>In the literature school.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Quorsum sic properas?</p>
<en-p>Where are you hurrying to now?</en-p>
<p>Ru. Domum versus.</p>
<en-p>Towards home.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Quid domi ages?</p>
<en-p>What will you do at home?</en-p>
<p>Ru. Adornabo mensam.</p>
<en-p>I’ll set the table.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Tam mane prandes?</p>
<en-p>You have lunch so early?</en-p>
<p>Ru. Obsequor parenti.</p>
<en-p>I’m doing what my dad wants.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Facis ut te decet.</p>
<en-p>You’re doing what’s right.</en-p>
<p>Ru. Abeo, tu vale.</p>
<en-p>I’m going; take care.</en-p>
<p>Qu. Tu quoque vale.</p>
<en-p>You take care, too.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XVI</h2>
<head>Dum Instruitur Mensa</head>
<en-head>While the Table Is Set</en-head>
<speakers>Remigius, Sebaldus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Re. Puer, ubi es?</p>
<en-p>Where are you, boy?</en-p>
<p>Se. Adsum, quid me vis?</p>
<en-p>I’m here; what do you want?</en-p>
<p>Re. Instrue mensam.</p>
<en-p>Set the table.</en-p>
<p>Se. Est tempus prandio?</p>
<en-p>Is it time for lunch?</en-p>
<p>Re. Est, quando sic libet.</p>
<en-p>It is, when it so pleases.</en-p>
<p>Se. Recte curabitur.</p>
<en-p>It will be taken care of properly.</en-p>
<p>Re. Porrige cultros.</p>
<en-p>Get out the knives.</en-p>
<p>Se. In promptu sunt.</p>
<en-p>They are ready.</en-p>
<p>Re. Da mappas manuarias.</p>
<en-p>Give the napkins.</en-p>
<p>Se. Et istae adsunt.</p>
<en-p>And those are here.</en-p>
<p>Re. Adpone salinum.</p>
<en-p>Set up the salt shaker.</en-p>
<p>Se. Prius sale implebo.</p>
<en-p>First I’ll fill it with salt.</en-p>
<p>Re. Elue calices.</p>
<en-p>Clean the glasses.</en-p>
<p>Se. Dudum lavi.</p>
<en-p>I just now washed them.</en-p>
<p>Re. Adfer orbes.</p>
<en-p>Bring over the plates.</en-p>
<p>Se. In scamno iacent.</p>
<en-p>They’re lying on the stool.</en-p>
<p>Re. Et corbem cocleariam.</p>
<en-p>And the spoon basket.</en-p>
<p>Se. E paxillo pendet.</p>
<en-p>It’s hanging on the peg.</en-p>
<p>Re. Apta circulum.</p>
<en-p>Set up the soup plate.</en-p>
<p>Se. Nunquid aliud vis?</p>
<en-p>Do you want anything else?</en-p>
<p>Re. Nunc mores discas.</p>
<en-p>Now you should learn manners.</en-p>
<p>Se. Quos mores discam?</p>
<en-p>What manners should I learn?</en-p>
<p>Re. Quos in mensa serves.</p>
<en-p>The ones you should mind at the table.</en-p>
<p>Se. Rogo me doceas.</p>
<en-p>I ask you to teach me.</en-p>
<p>Re. Perlubens hoc faciam.</p>
<en-p>I will do that very gladly.</en-p>
<p>Se. Ego auscultabo.</p>
<en-p>I will listen.</en-p>
<p>Re. Ne me interpella.</p>
<en-p>Don’t interrupt me.</en-p>
<p>Se. Haud verbum faciam.</p>
<en-p>I won’t say a word.</en-p>
<p>Re. Primo ungues purga. Hinc manus lava. Mox Deo benedicas. 
  Deus pater noster caelestis benedicat nobis filiis suis et his 
  quae iam sumus sumpturi, per Christum dominum nostrum, Amen. 
  Post decenter accumbe. Cibos carpe digitis. Ne conde volā. 
  Primus ne esto esu. Nec primum bibas. Cubitis ne te fulcias. 
  Erectus sede. Nec pandas brachia. Non bibas avide. Nec mandas 
  avide. Proxima te carpe. In orbe ne morare. Alios ne inspicito. 
  Bibiturus os terge. Non manu, sed mappula. Morsa ne redintinge. 
  Ne linge digitos. Nec ossa rodas. Quaeque scinde cultro. 
  Os non perungas. Digitos saepe terge. Nares ne fode. Non 
  rogatus taceas. Quod satis est ede. Cum satur es surge. Rursus 
  lava manus. Mensalia tolle. Deo gratias age. Qui nos creavit, 
  redemit et pavit, illi gratias agimus sempiternas, per Iesum 
  Christum dominum nostrum, Amen.</p>
<en-p>First clean your nails. Then wash your hands. Next praise God. “May God, our heavenly Father, bless us his children and these things we are about to receive, through Christ Our Lord, amen.” After that sit down properly. Take food with your fingers. Don’t hold it in your fist. Don’t be the first to eat. And don’t drink first. Don’t lean on your elbows. Sit straight. Don’t spread out your arms. Don’t drink greedily. And don’t chew greedily. Take the things closest to you. Don’t get absorbed in your plate. Don’t stare at other people. Wipe your mouth before you drink. Not with your hand; with your napkin. Don’t double-dip. Don’t lick your fingers. And don’t gnaw the bones. Cut things with your knife. Don’t smear stuff on your mouth. Wipe your fingers often. Don’t pick your nose. Be quiet if you’re not asked anything. Eat what is sufficient. When it’s enough, get up. Wash your hands again. Pick up the stuff on the table. Give thanks to God. “Who has created us, redeemed, and fed, to Him we give thanks forever, through Jesus Christ Our Lord, amen.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XVII</h2>
<head>A Prandio Redeuntium In Scholam</head>
<en-head>Returning to School from Lunch</en-head>
<speakers>Simon, Titus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Si. Quid geris in sinu?</p>
<en-p>What are you carrying in your pocket?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Merendam meam.</p>
<en-p>My snack.</en-p>
<p>Si. Ego nihil attuli.</p>
<en-p>I didn’t bring anything.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Quid autem edes?</p>
<en-p>But what will you eat?</en-p>
<p>Si. Emam mihi panem.</p>
<en-p>I will buy myself some bread.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Habes pecuniam?</p>
<en-p>You have money?</en-p>
<p>Si. Obolum habeo.</p>
<en-p>I’ve got a quarter.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Quis tibi hunc dedit?</p>
<en-p>Who gave it to you?</en-p>
<p>Si. Pater meus dedit.</p>
<en-p>My dad gave it.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Pium habes patrem.</p>
<en-p>You have a nice dad.</en-p>
<p>Si. Qualem tu habes?</p>
<en-p>What sort do you have?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Admodum durum.</p>
<en-p>Very strict.</en-p>
<p>Si. In rem tuam est.</p>
<en-p>That’s your business.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Mallem alium.</p>
<en-p>I’d rather have another.</en-p>
<p>Si. Stulte loqueris.</p>
<en-p>You’re talking like an idiot.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Sic mihi excidit.</p>
<en-p>That’s how it happened to me.</en-p>
<p>Si. Perires licentia.</p>
<en-p>You’d hurt yourself with your complaining.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XVIII</h2>
<head>In Schola Ludentium</head>
<en-head>Playing in School</en-head>
<speakers>Timothaeus, Vitus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ti. Vae nobis Vite.</p>
<en-p>Woe upon us, Vitus.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Quid est? quid tremis?</p>
<en-p>What is it? Why are you shaking?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Ego et tu perimus.</p>
<en-p>You and I perish.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Quid ita? qua de causa?</p>
<en-p>Why is it so? For what reason?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Praeceptor venit.</p>
<en-p>The teacher is coming.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Quid ex te audio?</p>
<en-p>What do I hear from you?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Vae nostris natibus.</p>
<en-p>Woe to our bottoms.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Ubi is est obsecro?</p>
<en-p>Where is he, I beseech you?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Per gradus ascendit.</p>
<en-p>He’s coming up the stairs.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Quis id ait? quis vidit?</p>
<en-p>Who says so? Who saw him?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Egomet inquam vidi.</p>
<en-p>I myself saw him, I say.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Viditne nos ludere?</p>
<en-p>Did he see that we’re playing?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Id est quod timeo.</p>
<en-p>That’s what I’m afraid of.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Quid ergo agemus?</p>
<en-p>So what will we do?</en-p>
<p>Ti. Amove orbiculos.</p>
<en-p>Get rid of the tiddly-winks.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Recte admones.</p>
<en-p>That’s a good idea.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Explicemus libros.</p>
<en-p>Let’s open our books.</en-p>
<p>Vi. Certe astutus es.</p>
<en-p>You’re definitely smart.</en-p>
<p>Ti. Sic rebit nos discere.</p>
<en-p>That way he’ll think we’re learning.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XIX</h2>
<head>De Dimissione A Literis</head>
<en-head>Dismissal from School</en-head>
<speakers>Ulysses, Xanthus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ul. Io gaudete sodales.</p>
<en-p>Yeah, let’s have fun, guys.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Quid est quod sic gestis?</p>
<en-p>What is it that you’re acting that way?</en-p>
<p>Ul. Sunt nobis feriae.</p>
<en-p>We have free days.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Quas dicis ferias?</p>
<en-p>What free days are you talking about?</en-p>
<p>Ul. Otium a litteris.</p>
<en-p>A break from literature.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Quando otiabimur?</p>
<en-p>When will we have our break?</en-p>
<p>Ul. Hodie a prandio.</p>
<en-p>Today, starting from lunch.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Ergo ludemus.</p>
<en-p>So we’ll play a game.</en-p>
<p>Ul. Quidnam ludemus?</p>
<en-p>What will we play?</en-p>
<p>Xa. Ludemus globulis.</p>
<en-p>We’ll play with marbles.</en-p>
<p>Ul. Ludus puerilis est.</p>
<en-p>That’s a kids’ game.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Quem tu ludum malles?</p>
<en-p>What game do you prefer?</en-p>
<p>Ul. Decertemus saltu.</p>
<en-p>Let’s have a jumping contest.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Hunc ludum odi.</p>
<en-p>I hate that game.</en-p>
<p>Ul. Quanam de causa?</p>
<en-p>What’s the reason?</en-p>
<p>Xa. Quia pedes lassat.</p>
<en-p>Because it makes my feet tired.</en-p>
<p>Ul. Annon pudet te?</p>
<en-p>Aren’t you ashamed of that?</en-p>
<p>Xa. Cuius me puderet?</p>
<en-p>What should I be ashamed of?</en-p>
<p>Ul. Quod tam piger es.</p>
<en-p>That you’re so lazy.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Certe piger non sum.</p>
<en-p>I am totally not lazy.</en-p>
<p>Ul. Quin ergo saltabis?</p>
<en-p>So then why won’t you jump?</en-p>
<p>Xa. Cave ne provoces.</p>
<en-p>Be careful you don’t start a fight.</en-p>
<p>Ul. Immo te adiuro.</p>
<en-p>No, I dare you.</en-p>
<p>Xa. Videbis quid possim.</p>
<en-p>You’ll see what I can do.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XX</h2>
<head>Litigantium De Sessione</head>
<en-head>Fighting Over a Seat</en-head>
<speakers>X. Y.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>X. Apage te hinc.</p>
<en-p>Get out of here.</en-p>
<p>Y. Satis imperiose.</p>
<en-p>You’re bossy enough.</en-p>
<p>X. Hic mihi locus est.</p>
<en-p>This is my spot.</en-p>
<p>Y. Atqui ego nego.</p>
<en-p>But I say otherwise.</en-p>
<p>X. Prior hic sedi.</p>
<en-p>I sat here first.</en-p>
<p>Y. Cur autem surrexisti?</p>
<en-p>But why did you get up?</en-p>
<p>X. Negotium mihi fuit.</p>
<en-p>I had to do something.</en-p>
<p>Y. Quid signi posuisti?</p>
<en-p>What sort of marker did you set?</en-p>
<p>X. Non vides librum?</p>
<en-p>You don’t see the book?</en-p>
<p>Y. Liber istic iacet.</p>
<en-p>The book’s lying over there.</en-p>
<p>X. At tu semovisti.</p>
<en-p>But you moved it away.</en-p>
<p>Y. Id factum pernego.</p>
<en-p>I deny doing so.</en-p>
<p>X. Quin tandem cedes?</p>
<en-p>So why don’t you go away?</en-p>
<p>Y. Tu me vi extrudes?</p>
<en-p>Are you going to throw me out by force?</en-p>
<p>X. Nisi volens cesseris.</p>
<en-p>Unless you’ll go away willingly.</en-p>
<p>Y. Hoc dicam magistro.</p>
<en-p>I’ll tell the teacher.</en-p>
<p>X. Susque deque fero.</p>
<en-p>I don’t care.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XXI</h2>
<head>Invitantium Se Invicem</head>
<speakers>Y. Z.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Y. Cras ad me veni.</p>
<en-p>Come visit me tomorrow.</en-p>
<p>Z. Metuo ut possim.</p>
<en-p>I’m afraid I can’t.</en-p>
<p>Y. Cur non possis?</p>
<en-p>Why could’t you?</en-p>
<p>Z. Domi manendum est.</p>
<en-p>I have to stay home.</en-p>
<p>Y. Quid negotii est?</p>
<en-p>What sort of work is there?</en-p>
<p>Z. Oportet scribere.</p>
<en-p>I have to write.</en-p>
<p>Y. Scribito perendie.</p>
<en-p>Write the day after tomorrow.</en-p>
<p>Z. Nihil polliceor.</p>
<en-p>I’m not promising anything.</en-p>
<p>Y. Sic colis socium.</p>
<en-p>That’s how you take care of a friend.</en-p>
<p>Z. Culpa non est mea.</p>
<en-p>It’s not my fault.</en-p>
<p>Y. Posses si velles.</p>
<en-p>You could if you would.</en-p>
<p>Z. Vellem si possem.</p>
<en-p>I would if I could.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XXII</h2>
<head>De Studio Interrogantium</head>
<en-head>Asking About Hobbies</en-head>
<speakers>Abraham, Briccius.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Ab. Quid a cena facis?</p>
<en-p>What do you do after dinner?</en-p>
<p>Br. Cupis hoc scire?</p>
<en-p>You want to know?</en-p>
<p>Ab. Ideo sciscitor.</p>
<en-p>That’s why I’m asking.</en-p>
<p>Br. Post cibum deambulo.</p>
<en-p>I go for a walk after dinner.</en-p>
<p>Ab. Quid postea agis?</p>
<en-p>What do you do afterwards?</en-p>
<p>Br. Audita repeto.</p>
<en-p>I go over the lectures.</en-p>
<p>Ab. Quomodo hoc facis?</p>
<en-p>How do you do that?</en-p>
<p>Br. Saepe relegendo.</p>
<en-p>By reading them again.</en-p>
<p>Ab. Quid si quid excidit?</p>
<en-p>What if something is missed?</en-p>
<p>Br. Disco postridie.</p>
<en-p>I learn it the next day.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XXIII</h2>
<head>De Absentia A Schola</head>
<en-head>About Being Gone From School</en-head>
<speakers>Benedictus, Christophorus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Be. Ubi heri fueras?</p>
<en-p>Where had you been yesterday?</en-p>
<p>Ch. Quonam tempore?</p>
<en-p>What time?</en-p>
<p>Be. Statim a prandio.</p>
<en-p>Right after lunch.</en-p>
<p>Ch. Domi meae lavi.</p>
<en-p>I took a bath at home.</en-p>
<p>Be. Quam diu lavisti?</p>
<en-p>How long did you take a bath?</en-p>
<p>Ch. Totam ferme horam.</p>
<en-p>Almost a whole hour.</en-p>
<p>Be. Quis tecum lavit?</p>
<en-p>Who took a bath with you?</en-p>
<p>Ch. Parentes mei.</p>
<en-p>My parents.</en-p>
<p>Be. Lotus quid feceras?</p>
<en-p>What did you do after your bath?</en-p>
<p>Ch. Siccabam capillos.</p>
<en-p>I dried my hair.</en-p>
<p>Be. Cur non ibas in scholam?</p>
<en-p>Why didn’t you go to school?</en-p>
<p>Ch. Pater prohibebat.</p>
<en-p>My dad said no.</en-p>
<p>Be. Cur prohibebat?</p>
<en-p>Why did he say no?</en-p>
<p>Ch. Nam caput madebat.</p>
<en-p>My head was dripping wet.</en-p>
<p>Be. Delicatus puer es.</p>
<en-p>You’re a pathetic kid.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XXIV</h2>
<head>Mutuo Gratulantium Sibi</head>
<speakers>Cyrillus, Donatus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Cy. Unde iam prorepis?</p>
<en-p>Where did you just crawl out of?</en-p>
<p>Do. E domo mea.</p>
<en-p>From my house.</en-p>
<p>Cy. Diu te non vidi.</p>
<en-p>I haven’t seen you in a long time.</en-p>
<p>Do. Et ego te diutius.</p>
<en-p>And I haven’t seen you longer.</en-p>
<p>Cy. Valuistine bene?</p>
<en-p>Have you been doing well?</en-p>
<p>Do. Optime valui.</p>
<en-p>I have been extremely well.</en-p>
<p>Cy. Aedepol, gaudeo.</p>
<en-p>Well, that’s great.</en-p>
<p>Do. Ut tu autem vales?</p>
<en-p>But how are you doing?</en-p>
<p>Cy. Admodum belle.</p>
<en-p>Very well.</en-p>
<p>Do. Et ipsum gaudeo.</p>
<en-p>And I’m glad to hear it.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XXV</h2>
<head>Agnoscentium Sese In Ludo</head>
<en-head>Recognizing Each Other in School</en-head>
<speakers>Simon, Petrus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Si. Quod tibi nomen est?</p>
<en-p>What’s your name?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Mihi nomen est Petro.</p>
<en-p>My name is Peter.</en-p>
<p>Si. Qui sis non novi.</p>
<en-p>I don’t know who you are.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Non me novisti?</p>
<en-p>You don’t know me?</en-p>
<p>Si. Non negem si noverim.</p>
<en-p>I wouldn’t deny if I did.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Oblitusne es mei?</p>
<en-p>Have you forgotten me?</en-p>
<p>Si. Ante nunquam te vidi.</p>
<en-p>I have never seen you before.</en-p>
<p>Pe. At tamen agnosces.</p>
<en-p>But you will acknowledge me.</en-p>
<p>Si. Sanus hercle non es.</p>
<en-p>You definitely aren’t well.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Egone, an tu magis?</p>
<en-p>I’m not, or are you instead?</en-p>
<p>Si. Ubi te novissem?</p>
<en-p>Where did I know you?</en-p>
<p>Pe. In ludo literario.</p>
<en-p>In literature school.</en-p>
<p>Si. Fuisti condiscipulus?</p>
<en-p>Were you a fellow student?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Ita, fere biennium.</p>
<en-p>Yes, for almost two years.</en-p>
<p>Si. Sine mecum recolam.</p>
<en-p>Let me think about it.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Agnosce cicatricem.</p>
<en-p>Recognize this scar.</en-p>
<p>Si. Hanc tibi incusseram.</p>
<en-p>I had made that one for you.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Cum theca pennaria.</p>
<en-p>With a pen case.</en-p>
<p>Si. De cicatrice te novi.</p>
<en-p>I know you because of the scar.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Vides quod non insaniam.</p>
<en-p>You see that I am not crazy.</en-p>
<p>Si. De forma non novissem.</p>
<en-p>I wouldn’t have known you by what you look like.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XXVI</h2>
<head>Litigantium De Re Ablata</head>
<en-head>Fighting About Something Taken</en-head>
<speakers>Petronius, Theodorus.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Pe. Redde quod meum est.</p>
<en-p>Give back what’s mine.</en-p>
<p>Th. Quid vis reddam?</p>
<en-p>What do you want me to give back?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Quod surripuisti.</p>
<en-p>What you stole.</en-p>
<p>Th. Nihil tibi surripui.</p>
<en-p>I stole nothing from you.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Aufer cavillum.</p>
<en-p>Cut out the joking.</en-p>
<p>Th. Non equidem cavillor.</p>
<en-p>I’m definitely not joking.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Quin reddis tandem?</p>
<en-p>Why don’t you give it back, then?</en-p>
<p>Th. Nihil hercle sumpsi.</p>
<en-p>Look, I took nothing.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Ostende huc manus.</p>
<en-p>Here, show me your hands.</en-p>
<p>Th. Hem, ostendo eccas.</p>
<en-p>Hey, look, I’m showing them.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Quid abstulisti?</p>
<en-p>What did you take away?</en-p>
<p>Th. Equidem nihil abstuli.</p>
<en-p>I really didn’t take anything.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Excute manicam.</p>
<en-p>Shake out your sleeves.</en-p>
<p>Th. Tuo arbitratu.</p>
<en-p>As you say.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Inter vestes habes.</p>
<en-p>You have it in your clothes.</en-p>
<p>Th. Tenta qualubet.</p>
<en-p>Try anywhere you like.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Novi sycophantias.</p>
<en-p>I know your tricks.</en-p>
<p>Th. Pergis molestus esse?</p>
<en-p>You’re still going to be annoying?</en-p>
<p>Pe. Ablatum restitue.</p>
<en-p>Restore what’s been taken.</en-p>
<p>Th. Furti me adligas?</p>
<en-p>Are you accusing me of theft.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Non furti, sed fraudis.</p>
<en-p>Not of theft, but of lying.</en-p>
<p>Th. Ulciscar hanc iniuriam.</p>
<en-p>I’ll pay you back for this insult.</en-p>
<p>Pe. Et ego te ulciscar.</p>
<en-p>And I’ll pay you back.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

<section>
<h2>Dialogus XXVII</h2>
<head>Prodeuntium In Funus</head>
<en-head>Going to a Funeral</en-head>
<speakers>Thomas, Georgius.</speakers>
<spoken>
<p>Th. Adesdum Georgi?</p>
<en-p>Are you here, George?</en-p>
<p>Ge. Quid est? cur me vocas?</p>
<en-p>What is it? Why are you calling me?</en-p>
<p>Th. Est quod te volo.</p>
<en-p>There’s something I want you for.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Dictum puta.</p>
<en-p>Think about what you just said.</en-p>
<p>Th. Quid censes me velle?</p>
<en-p>What do you think I want?</en-p>
<p>Ge. Ut tecum ludam.</p>
<en-p>That I play a game with you.</en-p>
<p>Th. Tota erras via.</p>
<en-p>You’re wrong in every way.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Quid igitur est?</p>
<en-p>So then what is it?</en-p>
<p>Th. Tu divina.</p>
<en-p>Use your intuition.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Nescio divinare.</p>
<en-p>I don’t know how to use my intuition.</en-p>
<p>Th. In funus prodibimus.</p>
<en-p>We’re going out to a funeral.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Quod funus dicis?</p>
<en-p>What funeral are you talking about?</en-p>
<p>Th. Quod sit nescio.</p>
<en-p>I don’t know which it is.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Unde autem nosti?</p>
<en-p>But where did you learn about it?</en-p>
<p>Th. Praeceptor indixit.</p>
<en-p>The teacher announced it.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Qua hora efferetur?</p>
<en-p>What time will he be carried out?</en-p>
<p>Th. Puto septima.</p>
<en-p>At 7:00, I think.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Et ego prodibo.</p>
<en-p>And I’ll go out with you.</en-p>
<p>Th. Tu mecum ibis.</p>
<en-p>You’ll go with me.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Ero tibi comes.</p>
<en-p>I will accompany you.</en-p>
<p>Th. Nec frustra hoc peto.</p>
<en-p>And I don’t ask this pointlessly.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Cur autem petis?</p>
<en-p>So then why are you asking?</en-p>
<p>Th. Ut me doceas.</p>
<en-p>So you can teach me.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Quid te docerem?</p>
<en-p>What would I teach you?</en-p>
<p>Th. Vino benedicere.</p>
<en-p>To bless wine.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Anne dum adfers?</p>
<en-p>Are you now bringing some?</en-p>
<p>Th. Rem ipsam dicis.</p>
<en-p>You got that right.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Sic ego dicerem…</p>
<en-p>I would say this…</en-p>
<p>Th. Dic, iam ausculto.</p>
<en-p>Say it, I’m listening now.</en-p>
<p>Ge. Hoc vinum nobis faustum sit. Bono sit potus iste. Hoc vinum laeti bibite.</p>
<en-p>May this wine be auspicious for us. May the drink be for the good. Rejoice as you drink this wine.</en-p>
<p>Th. Quid sternutanti imprecer?</p>
<en-p>What do you pray for someone sneezing?</en-p>
<p>Ge. Sit tibi hoc foelix. Te deus servet.</p>
<en-p>May things be well for you. May God preserve you.</en-p>
<p>Th. Quid auspicanti aliquid?</p>
<en-p>What about for someone looking for omens?</en-p>
<p>Ge. Bono sit quod instituis. Bene vertat quod agis.</p>
<en-p>May what you are starting go well. May what you are doing turn out well.</en-p>
<p>Th. Quid proficiscenti?</p>
<en-p>What about for someone starting a journey?</en-p>
<p>Ge. Sit iter hoc foelix tibi. Perfauste solvas ancoram. Sit laetus tibi reditus.</p>
<en-p>May this trip be fortunate for you. May you loose your anchor very fortunately. May you have a happy return.</en-p>
<p>Th. Quid haec precanti referam?</p>
<en-p>What should I respond to someone saying such prayers?</en-p>
<p>Ge. Tantundem tibi reprecor.</p>
<en-p>I pray for the same to you.</en-p>
</spoken>
</section>

